{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563568"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16817"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.13,0.49,0.16,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67090"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4210"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67090"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with a two-year history of heavy menstrual bleeding. Her periods last seven days and she requires changing pads every hour on the heaviest days. She has previously tried tranexamic acid and a levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine device without improvement. She has two children and does not want any more pregnancies. She has iron deficiency anaemia requiring oral supplementation. She has no other medical history and takes no regular medications apart from iron tablets. She runs a busy business and bleeding is affecting her quality of life and work. She is concerned about any procedures that may have a lengthy recovery and impact on her ability to work. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 27 kg/m2. Pelvic examination reveals no abnormalities. Transvaginal ultrasound shows a normal-sized uterus with regular endometrium measuring 8 mm. Recent cervical co-testing and endometrial sampling are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Watchful waiting with iron supplementation","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Endometrial ablation","Uterine artery embolisation","Hysterectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with heavy menstrual bleeding that has failed first-line medical management including tranexamic acid and levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine device. Given her completed family, desire to avoid major surgery, and normal investigations, \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial ablation\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective definitive treatment for heavy menstrual bleeding but is associated with longer recovery time, higher complication rates, and this patient has specifically expressed a desire to avoid it. It would be more appropriate to try less invasive options first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered a first-line medical treatment, but given the failure of other medical management and the patient\u0027s age, it would not be the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine artery embolisation\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for the treatment of uterine fibroids, which have not been identified on imaging in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting with iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate given the severity of symptoms, impact on quality of life, and failure of previous management attempts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndometrial ablation is a minimally invasive procedure that destroys the endometrial lining, reducing or eliminating menstrual flow. It has a shorter recovery time compared to hysterectomy and can be performed as a day procedure. Success rates are around 80-90%, though some patients may require further treatment. It is contraindicated in women who desire future pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endometrial ablation is an appropriate second-line treatment for heavy menstrual bleeding when medical management has failed and fertility is no longer desired.","Endometrial ablation has a shorter recovery time and fewer complications compared to hysterectomy.","Patient preference and desire to avoid major surgery should be considered when selecting treatment options for heavy menstrual bleeding."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Endometrial ablation [Internet]. [cited 2024 Dec 3]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Endometrial-Ablation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T13:35:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T13:36:00+10:30"},"relationships":